, the mere existence of such power makes those subject to it unfree. Most Italians, following the lead of their elites, lack the minimal moral qualities of free people, such as respect for the Constitution, the willingness to obey laws, and the readiness to discharge civic duties. As Viroli demonstrates, they exhibit instead the characteristics of servility, including flattery, blind devotion to powerful men, an inclination to lie, obsession with appearances, imitation, buffoonery, acquiescence, and docility. Accompanying these traits is a marked arrogance that is apparent among not only politicians but also ordinary citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aLiberty. 0aPolitical corruptionzItaly. 0aPolitical ethicszItaly. 0aPower (Social sciences)zItaly. 0aSocial ethicszItaly. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aItalian history.  aItalian mores.  aItaly.  aSilvio Berlusconi.  aarbitrary power.  aarrogance.  ablind devotion.  acitizens.  acourt system.  acourt.  acynicism.  adependency.  adomination.  afear.  aindifference.  aliberty.  apolitical liberty.  apowerful men.  arepublican liberty.  asafety.  asecurity.  aself-respect.  aservants.  aservility.  aservitude.  asignore.  asubjects.  asuperior power.  aunfreedom.1 aShugaar, Antony.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400840274zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400840274423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400840274.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL